  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "This genealogy treats tabletop role-playing games as a convergence of several lineages rather than as a single invention. The form inherits from war gaming, improvisation, small-press publishing, and face-to-face group ritual all at once. For a sourced synthesis, see Tabletop Role-Playing Games.\nThe referee lineage. TTRPGs inherit a referee model from tabletop war gaming. One participant mediates hidden information, resolves edge cases, and adapts procedure to unfolding play. In role-playing games this role becomes broader than a war-game umpire: the game master not only arbitrates rules but also frames scenes, portrays non-player characters, and manages pacing.\n",
  "name": "Genealogy of Tabletop Role-Playing Games",
